Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

get_store_id_from_uri function will only verify the scheme of the backend, not if the file is really present, this would lead to an error if you use multiple backend of the same type (ex: 2 rbd backend). if the file is on the second backend, so the first one will be returned by your function, and glance will still trigger a 400 Invalid location when trying to effectively check the file later in the process.

I recommend to use :
"get_size_from_uri_and_backend(url, backend)" from glance_store instead, as it would really check the size of the file in the backend, and trigger an error is not found.

For me we need to look more at https://review.opendev.org/#/c/618932/2

Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Two things:

(1) something to look at noted inline

(2) I was reading over Victor's comment, and while I think you are correct about the rbd case, from looking at https://review.opendev.org/#/c/660340/, it looks like Victor would be right about at least the http store and the cinder store (I didn't look through all of them).  Maybe configuring multiple http stores is a weird case (though I'm not convinced of that), but I can see someone using multiple cinder stores.  I think this lazy update needs to be more robust.

Patch Set 6:

Too more things to say (sorry for that):
- Can't we put the lazy_update_store_info() in a utils function ? Because it is exactly the same code as the _update_store_in_location() function in https://review.opendev.org/#/c/660645 (I will move my test then)
- I agree that the RBD store should be ok with the url_prefix comparaison, but in case of ceph cluster not available at glance boot time, so you will return only "rbd://" as url_prefix, and you will have get the issue I explain previously, even though the ceph cluster is back online since. Does this code executed only at glance boot time or at every request ?

Patch Set 6:

> Too more things to say (sorry for that):
 > - Can't we put the lazy_update_store_info() in a utils function ?
 > Because it is exactly the same code as the _update_store_in_location()
 > function in https://review.opendev.org/#/c/660645 (I will move my
 > test then)
 > - I agree that the RBD store should be ok with the url_prefix
 > comparaison, but in case of ceph cluster not available at glance
 > boot time, so you will return only "rbd://" as url_prefix, and you
 > will have get the issue I explain previously, even though the ceph
 > cluster is back online since. Does this code executed only at
 > glance boot time or at every request ?
Hi Victor,

The _url_prefix will be set while initializing the stores. Stores are initialized at the time of boot as well as post, update, delete  requests as well. I have tested this with 2 ceph nodes and never encountered the issue you have mentioned.

Patch Set 6:

> (1 comment)
 > 
 > Two things:
 > 
 > (1) something to look at noted inline
 > 
 > (2) I was reading over Victor's comment, and while I think you are
 > correct about the rbd case, from looking at https://review.opendev.org/#/c/660340/,
 > it looks like Victor would be right about at least the http store
 > and the cinder store (I didn't look through all of them).  Maybe
 > configuring multiple http stores is a weird case (though I'm not
 > convinced of that), but I can see someone using multiple cinder
 > stores.  I think this lazy update needs to be more robust.

Hi Brian,

You are right, for cinder and http stores this can be problematic only in case of locations operation. This lazy update function is robust at the moment. In order to support cinder and http multiple stores for add/replace location case we need to change the driver implementation and append a uuid to each store instead of just creating the url prefix like cinder:// and http://. Also we need to change the consumer side like cinder or nova as well.
